title: MySQL Server Defaults
owner: MySQL
---


This topic describes the defaults that MySQL for Pivotal Cloud Foundry (PCF) applies to its Percona Server components.
There are other components that can be customized as well.

<table>
    <th>Name</th>
    <th>Property Name</th>
    <th>Default</th>
    <th>Notes</th>
    <tr>
    	<td><strong>Max Connections</strong></td>
        <td><code>max\_connections</code></td>
        <td>750 connections</td>
        <td>All service instances accept up to 750 connections.
            System processes count towards this limit.
        </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
    	<td><strong>Max Allowed Packet</strong></td>
        <td><code>max\_allowed\_packet</code></td>
        <td>256&nbsp;MB</td>
        <td>You can change this size in a session variable if necessary. </td>
    </tr>
     <tr>
    	<td><strong>Table Definition Cache</strong></td>
        <td><code>table\_definition\_cache</code></td>
        <td>8192</td>
        <td>For more information about updating this variable,
            see the [MySQL documentation](https://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/5.7/en/server-system-variables.html#sysvar_table_definition_cache).
        </td>
    </tr>
     <tr>
    	<td><strong>Reverse Name Resolution</strong></td>
        <td><code></code></td>
        <td>OFF</td>
        <td>
            Disabling reverse DNS lookups improves performance.
            MySQL for PCF uses user credentials, not hostnames, to authenticate access.
            Therefore, most deployments do not need reverse DNS lookups.<br>
            To enable reverse name resolution, clear this option.
        </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
    	<td><strong>Skip Symbolic Links</strong></td>
        <td><code></code></td>
        <td></td>
        <td>
            MySQL for PCF is configured to prevent the use of symlinks to tables. 
            This recommended security setting prevents users from manipulating files on the serverâ€™s file system. 
            For more information, see [Making MySQL Secure Against Attackers](https://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/5.7/en/security-against-attack.html)
        </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
    	<td><strong>MyISAM Recover Options</strong></td>
        <td><code>myisam\_recover\_options</code></td>
        <td>BACKUP, FORCE</td>
        <td>
            This setting enables MySQL for PCF to recover from most MyISAM problems without human intervention.
            For more information, see the [MySQL documentation](https://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/5.7/en/server-options.html#option_mysqld_myisam-recover-options).
        </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
    	<td><strong>Log Bin Trust Function Creators</strong></td>
        <td><code>log\_bin\_trust\_function\_creators</code></td>
        <td>ON</td>
        <td>
            This setting relaxes constraints on how MySQL writes stored procedures to the binary log.
            For more information, see the [MySQL documentation](https://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/5.7/en/stored-programs-logging.html).
        </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
    	<td>Event Scheduler</td>
        <td><code>event\_scheduler</code></td>
        <td>ON</td>
        <td>
            MySQL for PCF enables the event scheduler so users can create and use 
            events in their dedicated service instances.
        </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
    	<td>Lower Case Table Names</td>
        <td><code>lower\_case\_table\_names</code></td>
        <td>ON</td>
        <td>
            By default, all table names are case sensitive.
            This option can be modified on the [MySQL Configuration pane](./install-config.html#mysql).
            For more information about the use for lowercase table names,
            see the [MySQL documentation](https://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/5.7/en/identifier-case-sensitivity.html).
        </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
    	<td>Audit Log</td>
        <td><code></code></td>
        <td>OFF</td>
        <td>
            The MySQL audit log is off by default.
            When enabled on the [MySQL Monitoring pane](./install-config.html#monitoring),
            logs are written as CSVs to <code>/var/vcap/sys/log/mysql/mysql\_audit\_log</code> 
            as well as a remote syslog drain if it is enabled.
        </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
    	<td>InnoDB Buffer Pool Size</td>
        <td><code>innodb\_buffer\_pool\_size</code></td>
        <td>50% of the available memory</td>
        <td>Dynamically configured to be 50% of the available memory on each service instance.</td>
    </tr>  
     <tr>
    	<td>InnoDB Log File Size</td>
        <td><code>innodb\_log\_file\_size</code></td>
        <td>256&nbsp;MB</td>
        <td>MySQL for PCF clusters default to a log-file size of 256&nbsp;MB.</td>
    </tr> 
     <tr>
    	<td>InnoDB Log Buffer Size</td>
        <td><code>innodb\_log\_buffer\_size</code></td>
        <td>32&nbsp;MB</td>
        <td>MySQL for PCF defaults to 32&nbsp;MB to avoid excessive disk I/O when issuing large transactions.</td>
    </tr> 
    <tr>
    	<td>InnoDB Auto Increment Lock Mode</td>
        <td><code>innodb\_autoinc\_lock\_mode</code></td>
        <td>2</td>
        <td>
            Auto Increment uses "interleaved" mode. 
            This enables multiple statements to execute at the same time.
            There may be gaps in auto-incrementing columns.
        </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
    	<td>Collation Server</td>
        <td><code>collation\_server</code></td>
        <td><code>utf8\_general\_ci</code></td>
        <td>You can override this during a session.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
    	<td>Character Set</td>
        <td><code></code></td>
        <td><code>utf8</code></td>
        <td>Defaults all character sets. You can override this during a session.</td>
    </tr>  
  </table>
